no men who are going beyond machismo to a deeper understanding of women’s experiences and a commitment to ending gender oppression. This new Latino manhood is the subject of Beyond Machismo. Applying and expanding the concept of intersectionality developed by Chicana feminists, Aída Hurtado and Mrinal Sinha explain how the influences of race, class, ethnicity, sexuality, and gender shape Latinos’ views of manhood, masculinity, and gender issues in Latino communities and their acceptance or rejection of feminism. In particular, the authors show how encountering Chicana feminist writings in college, as well as witnessing the horrors of sexist oppression in the United States and Latin America, propels young Latino men to a feminist consciousness. By focusing on young, high-achieving Latinos, Beyond Machismo elucidates this social group’s internal diversity, thereby providing a more nuanced understanding of the processes by which Latino men can overcome structural obstacles, form coalitions across lines of difference, and contribute to movements for social justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aFeminismzUnited States. 0aMachismozLatin America. 0aMasculinityxSocial aspectszLatin America. 0aMenxEducationzLatin America. 0aMenzLatin AmericaxEconomic conditions. 0aMenzLatin AmericaxIdentity. 0aMenzLatin AmericaxSocial conditions. 0aMexican American womenxEthnic identity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAnzaldúa, Gloria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSinha, Mrinal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/30876940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477308783423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477308783/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEB